---
import Layout from "../layouts/Page.astro";
import Container from "../components/Container.astro";

const seo = {
  title: "Multiplier of Gains Calculator",
  description: "The Multiplier of Gains Calculator is a tool to help you calculate how many times you have gained in a given time period.",
};
---

<style>
  .hero__article {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
    min-height: 70vh;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .form-container {
    background-color: #f7f7f7;
    border-radius: 10px;
    padding: 30px;
    margin: 10px;
    max-width: 400px;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 15px;
  }

  .form-label {
    display: flex;
    gap: 10px;
    align-items: center;
  }

  .form-button {
    background-color: #4caf50;
    color: white;
    padding: 10px 20px;
    border: none;
    border-radius: 5px;
    cursor: pointer;
  }

  .form-button:hover {
    background-color: #45a049;
  }

  h3 {
    margin-bottom: 20px;
  }
</style>  

<Layout seo={seo}>
  <Container narrow>
    <article class="hero__article">
      <h3>Multiplier of Gains Calculator</h3>
      <form id="multiplierForm">
        <label for="initialValue">Initial Value:</label>
        <input
          type="number"
          id="initialValue"
          name="initialValue"
          step="any"
          required
        />
        <label for="finalValue">Final Value:</label>
        <input
          type="number"
          id="finalValue"
          name="finalValue"
          step="any"
          required
        />
        <button type="submit">Calculate</button>
      </form>
      <p id="result"></p>
    </article>
    <section>
      <h3>Understanding Multiplier of Gains</h3>
      <p>
        The Multiplier of Gains Calculator helps you determine how many times
        your initial investment has increased. It's a measure of growth, often
        used to compare the performance of different investments. Calculating
        the multiplier of gains is relatively simple. You divide the final value
        of your investment by its initial value.
      </p>
      <p>
        For example, if you initially invested $1,000 and it grew to $3,000, the
        multiplier of gains would be 3x. This means that your investment has
        tripled in value. The higher the multiplier, the better your investment
        performance. Keep in mind that this calculation does not take into
        account the time it took for your investment to grow, which is an
        essential factor when comparing different investments.
      </p>
      <h3>How the Multiplier of Gains Affects Your Investments</h3>
      <p>
        Understanding the multiplier of gains is crucial when evaluating your
        investments. It can help you make informed decisions about whether to
        continue holding an investment, sell it, or invest more. A high
        multiplier may indicate a successful investment strategy or a
        well-performing asset. Conversely, a low or negative multiplier suggests
        that your investment may not be performing as expected or that you might
        need to reconsider your strategy.
      </p>
      <p>
        The multiplier of gains is also useful for comparing the performance of
        various investments. By calculating the multiplier for each investment,
        you can determine which investments are outperforming others and
        potentially allocate more funds to those with higher multipliers.
      </p>
      <p>
        However, it's essential to remember that past performance does not
        guarantee future results. While the multiplier of gains can provide
        valuable insights, it's just one of many factors to consider when
        evaluating your investments. Always take a holistic approach,
        considering factors such as the investment's risk, fees, and your own
        financial goals and risk tolerance.
      </p>
    </section>
    <script>
      document
        .getElementById("multiplierForm")
        .addEventListener("submit", (event) => {
          event.preventDefault();
          const initialValue = parseFloat(
            event.target.elements.initialValue.value
          );
          const finalValue = parseFloat(event.target.elements.finalValue.value);

          function multiplierIncrease(initialValue, finalValue) {
            if (initialValue === 0) {
              return "Initial value cannot be zero.";
            }
            const multiplier = finalValue / initialValue;
            return multiplier.toFixed(2); // Format the result to 2 decimal places
          }

          const result = multiplierIncrease(initialValue, finalValue);
          document.getElementById(
            "result"
          ).innerHTML = `You made a ${result} x`;
        });
    </script>
  </Container>
</Layout>
